                            <comment id="14004887" author="apurtell" created="Wed, 21 May 2014 16:44:25 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 for 0.98. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14004903" author="ndimiduk" created="Wed, 21 May 2014 16:56:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;As I understand it, 2 flusher threads will mean more frequent flushes and thus more, smaller files. Should this be accompanied with an increase to hbase.hstore.blockingStoreFiles ? Basically, it moves the blocking pressure from memstore global limit to compaction queue?&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14004922" author="nkeywal" created="Wed, 21 May 2014 17:07:42 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;yes and no. No, because in theory there is no queue, so changing this setting changes nothing, except if one datanode is having issue. Yes, because in practice I&apos;ve seen this. There is a limit on the number of files. &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-11208&quot; title=&quot;Remove the hbase.hstore.blockingStoreFiles setting&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-11208&quot;&gt;HBASE-11208&lt;/a&gt; is about removing it, but this is too much of a change for a 0.98 default imho...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can see that the queuing is happening in the logs: if the actual flush size is much larger than the configured flush size, it means that you got queued.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14005122" author="ndimiduk" created="Wed, 21 May 2014 19:21:21 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;ACK.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;+1&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
